<hr class="css-44nrrx e1ypdxhw0">
<p data-component="the-world-in-brief-paragraph" class="css-1l5amll e1y9q0ei0"><b>Afghanistan </b>launched “large-scale offensive operations” along its border with <b>Pakistan. </b><a href="https://www.economist.com/asia/2025/08/21/the-world-is-learning-to-live-with-the-taliban" data-analytics="espresso_gobbets:link_1:gobbet_1">The Taliban</a> said the strikes were in retaliation against Pakistani attacks on Afghanistan on Sunday. Pakistan said those strikes targeted groups responsible for several deadly attacks on its territory, including a suicide-bombing in Islamabad, the capital, that killed at least 36 people.
</p>
<hr class="css-44nrrx e1ypdxhw0">
<p data-component="the-world-in-brief-paragraph" class="css-1l5amll e1y9q0ei0">The average <b>30-year-mortgage rate</b> in America fell below 6% for the first time since 2022. Borrowing costs have been gradually declining since the middle of 2025. Inflation has slowed, and the Federal Reserve cut interest rates three times in the second half of last year. Lower <a href="https://www.economist.com/finance-and-economics/2025/11/19/americas-huge-mortgage-market-is-slowly-dying" data-analytics="espresso_gobbets:link_2:gobbet_2">mortgage rates</a> could heat up <a href="https://www.economist.com/finance-and-economics/2025/08/10/americas-housing-market-is-shuddering" data-analytics="espresso_gobbets:link_3:gobbet_2">America’s housing market</a>, although their recent drop has not spurred home-buying.
</p>
<hr class="css-44nrrx e1ypdxhw0">
<p data-component="the-world-in-brief-paragraph" class="css-1l5amll e1y9q0ei0">Nuclear negotiations between <b>America </b>and <b>Iran </b>concluded in Geneva. Abbas Araghchi,<b> </b>Iran’s<b> </b>foreign minister, described them as one of the “most serious” yet. Badr Albusaidi, his Omani counterpart who was mediating the talks, said “significant progress” was made. Further discussions are expected to take place next week. Donald Trump has suggested <a href="https://www.economist.com/leaders/2026/02/26/donald-trump-is-at-risk-of-launching-a-war-without-purpose" data-analytics="espresso_gobbets:link_4:gobbet_3">America will attack Iran</a> if it does not negotiate a deal.
</p>
<hr class="css-44nrrx e1ypdxhw0">
<p data-component="the-world-in-brief-paragraph" class="css-1l5amll e1y9q0ei0">A <b>German </b>court suspended the domestic spy agency’s designation of <b>Alternative for Germany</b> <b>(<small>A</small>f<small>D</small>) </b>as an “extremist” organisation. The temporary ruling will allow the court to consider <a href="https://www.economist.com/europe/2026/02/05/how-remigration-is-penetrating-europes-political-mainstream" data-analytics="espresso_gobbets:link_5:gobbet_4">the hard-right party’s</a> appeal. The decision prevents authorities from keeping the party under targeted surveillance for now—a boon for the <small>A</small>f<small>D</small> ahead of upcoming state elections.
</p>
<hr class="css-44nrrx e1ypdxhw0">
<p data-component="the-world-in-brief-paragraph" class="css-1l5amll e1y9q0ei0"><b>Borge Brende</b>, the chief executive of the <b>World Economic Forum</b>, which organises the Davos meetings, resigned after it launched an investigation into his ties to Jeffrey Epstein. Files released by America’s Justice Department suggested that Mr Brende, a Norwegian, attended dinners with him. He has denied knowledge of Epstein’s crimes. <a href="https://www.economist.com/business/2026/02/05/jeffrey-epsteins-ghost-is-haunting-the-grand-old-men-of-capitalism" data-analytics="espresso_gobbets:link_6:gobbet_5">Several business leaders</a> have stepped down over similar links to Epstein.
</p>
<hr class="css-44nrrx e1ypdxhw0">
<p data-component="the-world-in-brief-paragraph" class="css-1l5amll e1y9q0ei0">A court in <b>Bangladesh </b>ordered the government to ask Interpol to issue a “red notice” against <b>Tulip Siddiq</b>, a British <small>MP</small>. The notice is a call for international assistance in her arrest. Bangladesh accuses Ms Siddiq of using her ties to her aunt—<a href="https://www.economist.com/asia/2026/02/19/can-bangladeshs-old-guard-build-a-new-democracy" data-analytics="espresso_gobbets:link_7:gobbet_6">Sheikh Hasina</a>, Bangladesh’s autocratic former prime minister—to influence a real-estate deal. Ms Siddiq denies wrongdoing and Britain does not have an extradition treaty with Bangladesh.
</p>
<hr class="css-44nrrx e1ypdxhw0">
<p data-component="the-world-in-brief-paragraph" class="css-1l5amll e1y9q0ei0"><b>Denmark’s </b>prime minister, Mette Frederiksen, called a parliamentary election to be held on March 24th. Support for Ms Frederiksen surged after she stood up to Mr Trump’s recent <a href="https://www.economist.com/briefing/2026/01/21/donald-trumps-grab-for-greenland-makes-no-sense" data-analytics="espresso_gobbets:link_8:gobbet_7">threats to annex Greenland</a>, an autonomous Danish territory. Still, concerns over the economy and her government’s efforts to boost defence spending could weigh on support for her Social Democratic Party.
</p>
<hr class="css-44nrrx e1ypdxhw0">
<p data-component="the-world-in-brief-paragraph" class="css-1l5amll e1y9q0ei0"><b>Figure of the day: 460,000</b>, the number of graduates produced each year by China’s elite “985” group of universities. <a href="https://www.economist.com/china/2026/02/24/how-to-get-rich-in-modern-china" data-analytics="espresso_gobbets:link_9:gobbet_8">Read the full story</a>.
</p>
<hr class="css-44nrrx e1ypdxhw0">
<p data-component="the-world-in-brief-paragraph" class="css-1l5amll e1y9q0ei0"><i>Understanding your wellbeing can be confusing. Cut through the noise with <a href="https://www.economist.com/newsletters/well-informed" data-analytics="espresso_gobbets:link_10:gobbet_9">Well Informed</a>, our weekly newsletter that assesses the scientific evidence behind health and wellness trends.</i>
</p>
