<div class="css-um96pz e1a1lgff0">
<h3 class="css-p09rkj e1pqka930">The Clintons’ date with Congress
</h3>
<p data-component="paragraph" class="css-1l5amll e1y9q0ei0">Bill and Hillary Clinton are headed to Capitol Hill. After months of stalling, the Clintons will answer a congressional committee’s questions about <a href="https://www.economist.com/interactive/international/2026/02/12/inside-epsteins-network" data-analytics="in_body:link_1:para_1">their ties</a> to <a href="https://www.economist.com/leaders/2026/02/12/the-epstein-files-tell-a-story-of-justice-denied" data-analytics="in_body:link_2:para_1">Jeffrey Epstein</a>, a dead <a href="https://www.economist.com/business/2026/02/05/jeffrey-epsteins-ghost-is-haunting-the-grand-old-men-of-capitalism" data-analytics="in_body:link_3:para_1">sex offender</a>. Mrs Clinton, who was Barack Obama’s secretary of state, will testify in a closed-door deposition on Thursday. When Mr Clinton follows on Friday, he will become the first former president to testify before a congressional panel since 1983.
</p>
<p data-component="paragraph" class="css-1l5amll e1y9q0ei0">Neither has been accused of wrongdoing by Epstein’s victims—and they deny any knowledge of his misdeeds. The Clintons’ lawyer claims that the committee, which is led by Republicans, is creating “a public spectacle for partisan purposes”. Mrs Clinton accuses the Justice Department of “slow-walking” the release of files related to <a href="https://www.economist.com/podcasts/2026/02/16/check-in-the-mail-analysis-of-epsteins-correspondence" data-analytics="in_body:link_4:para_2">Epstein</a>; she maintains that the Trump administration is engaged in a “cover-up”. Expect finger-pointing from all sides, but few revelations.
</p>
</div>
