<div class="css-um96pz e1a1lgff0">
<h3 class="css-p09rkj e1pqka930">Last chance for America and Iran
</h3>
<p data-component="paragraph" class="css-1l5amll e1y9q0ei0">The window for diplomacy is <a href="https://www.economist.com/middle-east-and-africa/2026/01/28/is-america-about-to-attack-iran" data-analytics="in_body:link_5:para_3">closing</a>. Officials from America and Iran will meet in Geneva on Thursday for a third round of negotiations aimed at preventing a war. The meeting comes as a second American aircraft-carrier is deployed near the Middle East. Satellite images show that many of the American warships usually docked in Bahrain are now out at sea. Donald Trump has promised to attack Iran if it does not negotiate a deal—though his objectives remain <a href="https://www.economist.com/middle-east-and-africa/2026/02/19/the-moment-of-reckoning-between-america-and-iran" data-analytics="in_body:link_6:para_3">unclear</a>.
</p>
<p data-component="paragraph" class="css-1l5amll e1y9q0ei0">Abbas Araghchi, Iran’s foreign minister, will probably offer concessions on the country’s uranium-enrichment programme. Some of Mr Trump’s Republican allies want to avoid a deal that boosts Iran’s embattled regime. So does Israel. Mr Trump made scant mention of Iran during his state-of-the-union address this week. He said Iran could <a href="https://www.economist.com/middle-east-and-africa/2026/02/04/donald-trump-wants-to-end-americas-half-century-conflict-with-iran" data-analytics="in_body:link_7:para_4">avoid conflict</a> if it promised not to build a bomb. But Iranian officials have offered similar assurances in the past; repackaging old rhetoric would hardly represent a breakthrough.
</p>
</div>
