<div class="css-um96pz e1a1lgff0">
<h3 class="css-p09rkj e1pqka930">A test in Manchester for Britain’s government
</h3>
<p data-component="paragraph" class="css-1l5amll e1y9q0ei0">Manchester will be the talk of <a href="https://www.economist.com/interactive/2025-british-politics" data-analytics="in_body:link_8:para_5">Westminster</a> on Thursday. Residents of Gorton and Denton, in the city’s south-east, are voting to replace Andrew Gwynne, a Labour <small>MP</small> who resigned in January. It should be a safe Labour seat. The constituency had the 38th-largest Labour majority in 2024. Gorton, part of inner Manchester, has a young population and a large group of <a href="https://www.economist.com/britain/2025/03/06/a-thorny-debate-in-britain-around-the-definition-of-islamophobia" data-analytics="in_body:link_9:para_5">Muslim voters</a>. Denton, a suburb, is mainly white and working class.
</p>
<p data-component="paragraph" class="css-1l5amll e1y9q0ei0">Yet the Labour government’s unpopularity opens up opportunities for rivals. Reform <small>UK</small> and the Green Party are pouring resources into the constituency. Opinion polls indicate that all three parties stand a chance. The by-election is especially risky for the prime minister, Sir Keir Starmer, who prevented <a href="https://www.economist.com/britain/2026/01/27/blighty-newsletter-the-biggest-winners-of-the-andy-burnham-debacle" data-analytics="in_body:link_10:para_6">Andy Burnham</a>, the Greater Manchester mayor and a potential <a href="https://www.economist.com/britain/2026/02/11/the-alternatives-to-sir-keir" data-analytics="in_body:link_11:para_6">rival to lead the party</a>, from standing as the Labour candidate. A Labour loss in&nbsp;Gorton and Denton would be bad for Sir Keir; a victory&nbsp;by Mr Burnham might have threatened him more.
</p>
</div>
</div>
