<div class="css-um96pz e1a1lgff0">
<h3 class="css-p09rkj e1pqka930">Baidu takes the wheel
</h3>
<p data-component="paragraph" class="css-1l5amll e1y9q0ei0">Baidu, a Chinese search-engine giant, has a bad reputation at home. Many young Chinese blame it for turning the national internet into an ad-clogged cesspool. They ridicule its apps, which they say are unusable. Although Baidu was the first company to release a Chinese large language model for consumer use, called Ernie, it lags behind those created by competitors such as Alibaba, Tencent and ByteDance, the owner of TikTok.
</p>
<p data-component="paragraph" class="css-1l5amll e1y9q0ei0">Yet the picture is not entirely bleak. Baidu’s <a href="https://www.economist.com/business/2025/11/24/the-self-driving-taxi-revolution-begins-at-last" data-analytics="in_body:link_12:para_8">driverless-taxi service</a>, Apollo Go, has been pushing aggressively into foreign countries, most recently Dubai (in partnership with <a href="https://www.economist.com/business/2025/08/07/uber-is-readying-itself-for-the-driverless-age-again" data-analytics="in_body:link_13:para_8">Uber</a>, an American ride-hailing firm). It is also eyeing launches in Britain and Germany (with Lyft, another ride-hailing app) this year. When Baidu reports its full-year results on Thursday, investors will look for signs that China’s search-engine titan is now a robotaxi champion-in-waiting.
</p>
